"The dwarven clan of the Duhelarym founded a great city underneath Lake Everspring, some five thousand years ago. As elves and humans gradually settled along the Azure Coast, new opportunities of trade for the dwarves were available. Thus, they           ¸constructed a fortress-tower on the small island that lies in the middle of the lake, which served not only as a trading post but also as a first line of defense. As kingdoms and cities were born and later destroyed, the duhelarym profited greatly from   ˙trade and were renowned for their exquisite craftmanship in metals and gems. Their undercity, Duhelarholme, acquired many names in those time - the humans called it Tora-Khaar and the elves called it Arkelonia, for example. Interestingly, the dwarves     ˙were excedingly overprotective of their holme, refusing anyone other then duhelarym dwarves to enter it - even excluding dwarves from other clans. This self-imposed isolation eventually cost them dearly, for they mined too deep in the underearth and,     ¸according to legends, awoke some sort of great evil. No help was sent to the dwarves, and much of what happened really remains folklore at best, because the dwarves were too secretive about their affairs. One thing is certain: they never asked for help   ˝and they were forced to abandon Duhelarholme. Again, legends say that only a few dozen kins of the clan survived whatever they awoke, deep down in the underearth. Since then, the undercity has been pretty much forgotten, whereas the fortress-tower built  ˙by the duhelarhym would be occupied often by mages, lords and would-be warlords. Today, this place remains barely standing and is known as Grag Keep. Legends insist that the means to enter lost Duhelarholme are to be found in Grag Keep - hence, there     çare many scholars and mages, seeking knowledge or power, are eager to know more of such means to enter Duhelarholme and plunder its secrets."                                                                   